The electricity distribution companies (DisCos) have said that the suspension of the proposed service reflective tariff which was to come into effect on Wednesday was initiated by the National Assembly (NASS) on Monday due to their concerns on its timing and what they saw as lapses in the workability of the plan within the sector. The Association of Nigerian Electricity Distributors (ANED) made this clarification in a statement signed by its executive director, Research and Advocacy, Barr. Sunday Oduntan, in a response to a news story published by a national daily, claiming the DisCos lobbied for the postponement. “The members of the National Assembly are representatives of the people. Based on the feedback they have been getting from their constituents, mainly around the difficult financial realities, they called for a meeting which we attended and they tabled their concerns. “The story published  actually insinuates that the leadership of the National Assembly can easily be manipulated by anyone or group of people. “DisCos have spent the last couple of weeks carrying out massive sensitisation across different platforms preparing their customers for the new service reflective tariff as instructed by the Nigeria Electricity Regulatory Commission (NERC). DisCos have also been on the forefront of the call for a reviewed tariff for years,” Oduntan said. July 1, 2020 was picked as the commencement date for a new service delivery-based tariff regime. Based on the recommendation of the NASS leadership, the new regime should take effect from the first quarter of 2021. issued earlier, accused NERC of feigning ignorance in the public about the July 1 tariff increase after approving of it, by writing to each of the 11 DisCos not to link the commission to the decision in the public place. 